/rjoseph.htm |title=Rohan Joseph |publisher=Rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Lakshman Joseph|de Saram}}\n| Violinist, composer\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>[http://sundaytimes.lk/120219/Plus/plus_01.html Lankan composer scores big with Hollywood set]</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Ranidu|Lankage}}\n| Musician\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Krishan|Maheson}}\n| Musician, singer\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Dushyanth|Weeraman}}\n| Musician, actor\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|J. L. K.|van Dort}}\n| 19th-century painter\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>[http://www.island.lk/2003/05/11//featur01.html Running in the family... with brush and palette]</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Rukshan|Perera}}\n| Musician\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>[http://sundaytimes.lk/110102/Magazine/sundaytimesmagazine_04.html A feast for fans from Rukshan]</ref>\n|}\n\n==Activists==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:*;\" | Name\n! style=\"width:65%;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notability\n! style=\"width:*;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Reference(s)\n|-\n| {{sortname|Ajith C. S.|Perera}}\n| [[List of disability rights activists|Disability rights activist]], [[Chief executive officer|Chief Executive]] / [[chief operating officer|Secretary-General]]\u2013 [[Idiriya]] (2016&ndash;present)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite news | last = Perera | first = Ajith C. S. | title = Cricket where Everybody is Included | work = Features Page 8 | publisher = Upali Newspapers - The Island | date = 19 August 2008 | url = http://www.island.lk/2008/08/19/features3.html | accessdate = 30 January 2009 | quote= Although now a wheelchair user, Perera remains very much 'Not Out' as a pioneer disability activist, promoting ''Environments that are Accessible and dis-Abled Friendly'' especially at Sports venues.}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Bala|Tampoe}}\n| [[General Secretary]] of the [[Ceylon Mercantile Union|Ceylon Mercantile, Industrial and General Workers Union]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Percy|Wickremasekera}}\n| [[General Secretary]] of the [[United Corporations and Mercantile Union]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Kumar|Ponnambalam}}\n| Leader of [[All Ceylon Tamil Congress]], [[1982 Sri Lankan presidential election|Presidential candidate (1982)]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|}\n\n==Religion==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:*;\" | Name\n! style=\"width:65%;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notability\n! style=\"width:*;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Reference(s)\n|-\n| {{sortname|Lakdasa|De Mel}}\n| First [[Bishop of Kurunegala]] (1950&ndash;1962), last [[Metropolitan Bishop]] of India, Pakistan, Burma and Ceylon (1962&ndash;1970)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/10/28/fea03.html |title=Rev. Lakdasa de Mel: inspiring legend of Baddegama |publisher=Dailynews.lk |date=28 October 2002 |accessdate=10 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604225909/http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/10/28/fea03.html |archivedate=4 June 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Harold|de Soysa}}\n| First Ceylonese [[Bishop of Colombo]] (1964&ndash;1971)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Roger|Herft}}\n| [[Anglican Diocese of Perth#Bishops and Archbishops of Perth|Archbishop of Perth]] (2005&ndash;2016), [[Bishop of Newcastle (Australia)|Bishop of Newcastle]] (1993&ndash;2005), [[Bishop of Waikato]] (1986&ndash;1992)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Kollupitiye Mahinda Sangharakkhitha |Thera}}\n| Chief Incumbent [[Kelaniya Raja Maha Vihara]] (1992&ndash;?)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=\"Sangharakkhitha Thera\">{{cite web|url=http://sundaytimes.lk/080224/News/news0010.html |title=Kelani Vihara head appointed varsity prof |publisher=Sundaytimes.lk |date=24 February 2008 |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Lakshman|Wickremasinghe}}\n| [[Bishop of Kurunegala]] (1962&ndash;1983) \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Cyril|Abeynaike}}\n| [[Bishop of Colombo]] (1971&ndash;1977)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Kenneth|Fernando}}\n| [[Bishop of Colombo]] (1992&ndash;2001)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Duleep|De Chickera}}\n| [[Church of Ceylon|Anglican]] [[Bishop of Colombo]] (2001&ndash;2010)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Ivan|Corea}}\n| Rural Dean of Colombo\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| {{sortname|Francis Lorenz|Beven}}\n| [[Archdeacon]] of [[Jaffna Diocese of the Church of South India|Jaffna]] (1925&ndash;1935), [[Archdeacon]] of [[Diocese of Colombo|Colombo]] (1935&ndash;1947)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dutchburgherunion.org/genealogy/ancestry-a/JDBU%201959%20Vol%2049%20No%203%20p60-69%20-%20Arndt%20Ancestry(1).pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008052026/http://www.dutchburgherunion.org/genealogy/ancestry-a/JDBU%201959%20Vol%2049%20No%203%20p60-69%20-%20Arndt%20Ancestry(1).pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 October 2013 |title=Genealogy Of The Family Of Arndt Of Ceylon |accessdate=23 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dutchburgherunion.org/genealogy/ancestry-b/JDBU%201952%20Vol%2042%20No%203%20p114-121%20-%20Beven%20Ancestry(1).pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905041537/http://www.dutchburgherunion.org/genealogy/ancestry-b/JDBU%201952%20Vol%2042%20No%203%20p114-121%20-%20Beven%20Ancestry(1).pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 September 2012 |title=Genealogy Of The Family Of Bervent Of Ceylon |accessdate=23 February 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{sortname|Neranjan|Wijeyeratne}}\n| [[Diyawadana Nilame]] (Chief lay Custodian) [[Temple of the Tooth]], [[Kandy]] (1985&ndash;2005)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|}\n\n==Old Royalists in fiction==\nMany [[fictional characters]] have been described as Old Royalists. These include:\n* Carlaboy von Bloss from the novel ''[[Carl Muller|Once Upon a Tender Time]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nation.lk/2008/02/03/special6.htm |title=Sir Christopher Ondaatje looks back at the importance of Carl Muller's Trilogy |publisher=Nation.lk |date= |accessdate=2011-09-10}}</ref>\n* Allan from the novel (later made into a film) ''[[Kaliyugaya (novel)|Kaliyugaya]]''\n* Malin from the novel (later made into a film) ''[[Yuganthaya]]''\n* Mithra Dias from the novel ''[[Nihal De Silva|The Giniralla Conspiracy]]''<ref>[http://www.dailynews.lk/2005/09/02/fea05.htm Revolutionary ardour and its aftermath The Giniralla Conspiracy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070407211800/http://www.dailynews.lk/2005/09/02/fea05.htm |date=2007-04-07 }}</ref>\n* The [[revolutionary]] Kumudu Prasanna from the novel ''The Giniralla Conspiracy''\n* Janendra \"Janu\" Samarawickrama from the novel ''[[Madhubahashini Disanayaka Ratnayaka|There is Something I Have to Tell You]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Royal College Colombo Alumni}}\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo| ]]\n[[Category:Colombo-related lists|Royal College]]\n[[Category:Lists of Sri Lankan people by school affiliation|Royal College, Colombo]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Another non notable alumni- Undid revision 950694360 byAkarawita(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Royal_College_Colombo_alumni"}
{"title_page": "Petersburg Goobers", "text_new": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n| name = Petersburg Goobers\n| firstseason = 1885\n| lastseason = 1954\n| allyears =  1885\u20131886, 1894\u20131896, 1900, 1910-1921, 1923\u20131924, 1926\u20131928, 1941\u20131942, 1948\u20131951, 1954\n| city = Petersburg, Virginia\n| logo = \n| caplogo = \n| past class level ={{plainlist|\n*Class B (1895, 1920-1921, 1923\u20131924, 1926\u20131928)\n*Class C 1910\u20131919, 1941\u20131942 )\n*Class D (1900,  1923\u20131925, 1948\u20131951, 1954)\n}}\n| league =\n| conference = \n| division = \n| past league = {{plainlist|\n* [[Virginia League (1894\u201396)|Virginia League]] (1885\u20131886, 1894\u20131896)\n* [[Virginia League (1900)|Virginia League]] (1900)\n* [[Virginia League]] (1910\u20131921, 1923\u20131924, 1926\u20131928)\n* [[Virginia League (1939\u201342)|Virginia League]] (1941\u20131942)\n* [[Virginia League (1948\u201351)|Virginia League]] (1948\u20131951)\n* [[Piedmont League]] (1954)\n}}\n| pastnames = {{plainlist|\n*Petersburg (1885\u20131886)\n* Petersburg Farmers (1894\u20131896, 1900)\n* '''Petersburg Goobers''' (1910\u20131921, 1924)\n* Petersburg Trunkmakers (1923)\n* Petersburg Broncos (1926\u20131928)\n* Petersburg Rebels (1941\u20131942)\n* Petersburg Generals (1948\u20131950)\n* Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals (1951)\n* Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts (1954)\n}}\n| pastparks = {{plainlist|\n* Petersburg Ballfield (1885\u20131886, 1894\u20131896, 1900)\n* Parkinson Park (1910\u20131913)\n* McKenzie Street Park (1914, 1923\u20131925, 1948\u20131950)\n* Sherwood Park (1951, 1954) \n}}\n| pastmajorleague ={{plainlist|\n*[[St. Louis Cardinals]] (1923)\n*[[Cincinnati Reds]] (1954)\n}}\n| classchamps = \n| leaguechamps = '''5''' 1894, 1911, 1913, 1919, 1949\n| conferencechamps =  1941, 1951\n| divisionchamps = \n}}\nThe '''Petersburg Goobers''' was a primary name of the [[minor league baseball]] team representing [[Petersburg, Virginia]] from 1910\u20131921 and 1924. The Petersburg Goobers played in the [[Virginia League]]. Numerous Petersburg teams played in the Virginia League, beginning in 1885 and ending in 1951. Petersburg was a member of the 1954 [[Piedmont League]].\n\nPetersburg was an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] (1923) and [[Cincinnati Reds]] (1954).\n\n[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] member [[Sam Rice]] played for the 1914\u20131915 Petersburg Goobers.\n\n==History==\nMinor league baseball began in Petersburg in 1885, when Petersburg joined the [[Virginia League (1894\u201396)|Virginia League]]. Petersburg played in the Virginia League in 1885 and 1886.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg,_VA|title=Petersburg, VA - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Petersburg Farmers''' rejoined the six-team 1894 Virginia League, winning the 1894 Championship. The Petersburg Farmers finished 72-44 in the regular season to capture the title, as there were no league playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pf13738/y-1894|title=1894 Petersburg Farmers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-VIRL/y-1894|title=1894 Virginia League (VL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter finishing  55-69 (5th) in 1895, the Petersburg Farmers started 1896 with a 32\u201360 record. On August 13, 1896, the Petersburg Farmers moved to [[Hampton, Virginia]] to become the '''Hampton-Newport News Clamdiggers''' for the remainder of the season. The Virginia League folded after the 1896 season.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Virginia_League|title=Virginia League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pf13738/y-1896|title=1896 Petersburg Farmers/Hampton-Newport News Clamdiggers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref> \n\nThe Virginia League reformed in 1900, before folding after the season. The Petersburg Farmers were 8\u201326 when the team disbanded on June 11, 1900.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pf13738/y-1900|title=1900 Petersburg Farmers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Petersburg Goobers''' began play in the Virginia League in 1910, when the [[Portsmouth Truckers]] moved to Petersburg on July 5, 1910. The team finished 6th with a 43\u201368 record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Portsmouth_(VA)_Truckers|title=Portsmouth (VA) Truckers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-pt13898|title=Portsmouth Truckers Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Petersburg Goobers won the 1911 Virginia League Championship. Petersburg, also going by the \"Hustlers\" monkier in 1911, finished 1st at 68\u201351 to capture the championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ph13742/y-1911|title=1911 Petersburg Hustlers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe Goobers finished 2nd in the 1912 Virginia League with a 79\u201354 record. The 1913 Petersburg Goobers captured the Virginia League Championship with their 1st place finish and 89\u201346 record.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1912|title=1912 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1913|title=1913 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1914 Petersburg Goobers finished 5th at 60\u201374. In 1915 they were 6th at 40\u201384 in the Virginia League.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Goobers|title=Petersburg Goobers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] member [[Sam Rice]] played for the Petersburg Goobers in 1914-1915. His performance in 1914, while on furlough from the [[U.S. Navy]], led Petersburg owner Dr. D.H Leigh to reach out to Virginia Senators [[Thomas S. Martin]] and [[Claude A. Swanson]] and inquire about getting Rice discharged from the Navy. In 1912, Rice was in the preseason, playing for the [[Galesburg Pavers]] when his wife, two children, his parents and two sisters were killed in a tornado. Rice eventually quit baseball and enrolled in the Navy. In 1914, with the senators help, Rice was honorably discharged from the Navy. He pitched and played the outfield for Petersburg for the remainder of the 1914 season, when he had a 9-2 record and hit .310. Rice rejoined the Petersburg Goobers for the 1915 season. On July 28, 1915, [[History of the Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)|Washington Senators]] owner [[Clark Griffith]] purchased Rice from Leigh and Petersburg. Rice was in the major leagues the next day at age 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/593ed95f|title=Sam Rice &#124; Society for American Baseball Research|website=sabr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi|title=1914 Petersburg Goobers Statistics|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1916 Petersburg Goobers finished 54\u201368, 4th in the Virginia League.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nIn 1917, the Goobers were 6\u20138 when the Virginia League disbanded on May 15, 1917.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1917|title=1917 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe Virginia League disbanded again in mid-season in 1918. The Petersburg Goobers were 27\u201322 when the league disbanded in June, 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1918|title=1918 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe Petersburg Goobers captured the 1919 Virginia League Championship. The Goobers finished 1st in the regular season with a 62\u201347 record. The Virginia League had planned to hold playoffs, but disagreements led to the playoffs being cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1919|title=1919 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAfter finishing 3rd in 1920, with a 68\u201350 record, Petersburg relocated in mid-season of 1921. The Petersburg Goobers moved to [[Tarboro, North Carolina]] on August 2, 1921 after the franchise was forfeited, playing as the '''Tarboro Tarbabies'''. The 1921 Petersburg/Tarboro squad finished last with a 46\u201388 record.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi|title=1921 Petersburg Goobers/Tarboro Tarbabies Statistics|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nPetersburg returned to the Virginia League in 1923 as the '''Petersburg Trunkmakers''', an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. The Trucnkmakers finished 6th in the six-team league with a 43\u201381 record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Trunkmakers|title=Petersburg Trunkmakers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Petersburg Goobers moniker reappeared in 1924. The Goobers finished 46\u201389, last in the Virginia League. Petersburg folded after the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1924|title=1924 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe '''Petersburg Broncos''' rejoined the Virginia League in 1926. The Broncos finished 6th (66\u201387) and 2nd (72\u201361). On June 3, 1928, the Broncos were in 3rd place with a 15\u201327 record, when the Virginia League disbanded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Broncos|title=Petersburg Broncos - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe 1941 '''Petersburg Rebels''' returned to the Virginia League. The 1941 Rebels finished 66\u201353, 1st in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Lynchburg Senators swept the Petersburg Rebels 3 games to 0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pr13743/y-1941|title=1941 Petersburg Rebels Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Petersburrg Rebels finished 3rd (74\u201352) in 1941. The Virginia League suspended play after the 1941 season due to [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pr13743/y-1942|title=1942 Petersburg Rebels Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAfter World War II, the '''Petersburg Generals''' joined the reformed Virginia League in 1948 and advanced to the 1948 league finals. The Generals finished 73\u201362, 4th in the regular season. In the playoffs, Petersburg defeated the Suffolk Goobers 4 games to 2 and advanced. In the Finals, the Blackstone Barristers defeated the Petersburg Generals 4 games to 3. The 1948 attendance was 116,062.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13740/y-1948|title=1948 Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1949 Petersburg Generals won the Virginia League Championship. Petersburg finished 72\u201354, 2nd in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Petersburg Generals defeated the Emporia Nationals 4 games to 3. In the Finals, the Petersburg Generals  defeated the Franklin Kildees 4 games to 2 to win the cha,pionship. The 1949 season attendance was 76,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13740/y-1949|title=1949 Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Generals|title=Petersburg Generals - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1950, the Petersburg Generals returned to the Virginia League finals for the third consecutive season. The Generals finished 69\u201361, 2nd in the Virginia League regular season. In the playoffs, the Generals defeated the Elizabeth City Albemarles 4 games to 2. In the Finals, the Emporia Nationals defeated the Petersburg Generals 4 games to 2. The Petersburg season attendance was 43,508.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13740/y-1950|title=1950 Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1951, Petersburg merged with neighboring [[Colonial Heights, Virginia]]. The team moved to play home games at Shepherd Park in Colonial Heights. The '''Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals''' advanced to the 1951 Virginia League finals. The Generals finished 80\u201339, 1st in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals defeated the Suffolk Goobers 4 games to 1. In the Finals, the Elizabeth City Albemarles defeated Colonial Heights-Petersburg 4 games to 1. The 1951 season attendance was 35,146. The Virginia League permanently folded after the 1951 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-VIRL5/y-1951|title=1951 Virginia League (VL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cg11000/y-1951|title=1951 Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1954, the '''Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts''' played in the [[Piedmont League]] as an affiliate of the [[Cincinnati Reds]]. The team finished  62\u201378, tied for last in the Piedmont League. The team folded after the 1954 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-cc10999|title=Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Colonial_Heights-Petersburg_Colts|title=Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Piedmont_League|title=Piedmont League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts were succeeded in Petersburg by the [[Petersburg Generals]]. Reusing the previous moniker, the Generals became members of the [[Coastal Plain League]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==The ballparks==\nUntil 1900, Petersburg played at '''Petersburg Ballfield'''. The ballpark was located at the corner of West Washington (US 460 & US 1) & West Street, Petersburg, Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-2089|title=Petersburg Ballfield in Petersburg, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nPetersburg teams from 1910-1913 played at '''Parkinson Park'''. The ballpark was located on Canal Street, Petersburg, Virginia, near the [[Appomattox River]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-2090|title=Parkinson Park in Petersburg, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1914 to 1950, Petersburg played at '''McKenzie Street Park'''. McKenzie Street Park was located on McKenzie Street between North West Street & North Dunlop Street, Petersburg, Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-2091|title=McKenzie Street Park in Petersburg, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1951 and 1954, Colonial Heights-Petersburg played at '''Shepherd Park'''. Today, the Shepherd Stadium Baseball Complex is still in use. The address is 901 Meridian Avenue, Colonial Heights, Virginia 23834.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-583|title=Shepherd Stadium in Colonial Heights, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.virginia.org/listings/SportsVirginia/ShepherdStadiumBaseballComplex/|title=Shepherd Stadium Baseball Complex - Virginia Is For Lovers|website=www.virginia.org}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n===[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] alumni===\n*[[Sam Rice]] (1914\u20131915) Inducted 1963\n===Notable alumni===\n*[[Ken Ash]] (1926\u20131927)\n*[[Everett Booe]] (1910\u20131912)\n*[[Dick Burrus]] (1917)\n*[[Tommy Clarke]] (1920, MGR)\n*[[Guy Cooper]] (1913)\n*[[Art Corcoran]] (1921) NFL MLB player\n*[[Harry Damrau]] (1913\u20131914)\n*[[Harley Dillinger]] (1917)\n*[[Davey Dunkle]] (1895)\n*[[Gus Dundon]] (1896)\n*[[John Farrell (second baseman)|John Farrell]] (1894)\n*[[Brownie Foreman]] (1894\u20131895)\n*[[Bill Gardner (baseball)|Bill Gardner]] (1886)\n*[[Jimmy Grant]] (1948)\n*[[June Greene]] (1923)\n*[[Bill Hallman]] (1896)\n*[[Harry Hedgpeth]] (1912\u20131914)\n*[[Snake Henry]] (1916)\n*[[Izzy Hoffman]] (1900)\n*[[Jack Horner (baseball)|Jack Horner]] (1894)\n*[[Bill Jackson (first baseman)|Bill Jackson]] (1910)\n*[[Vic Keen]] (1918)\n*[[Mickey Keliher]] (1910\u20131911, 1915)\n*[[Enos Kirkpatrick]] (1910)\n*[[Frank Kitson (baseball)|Frank Kitson]] (1896)\n*[[Ed Konetchy]] (1924, MGR)\n*[[Tommy Leach]] (1896)\n*[[Doc McJames]] (1894\u20131895)\n*[[Billy Martin (shortstop)|Bill Martin]] (1921, MGR)\n*[[Amby McConnell]] (1919\u20131921) (1919, 1921, MGR)\n*[[Herm McFarland]] (1910)\n*[[Doc McJames]] (1895)\n*[[Rufus Meadows]] (1924)\n*[[George Mohart]] (1916)\n*[[Greg Mulleavy]] (1927)\n*[[Bert Myers]] (1894)\n*[[Vance Page]] (1928)\n*[[Dixie Parker]] (1918\u20131919)\n*[[Ed Porray]] (1915)\n*[[Doc Powers]] (1896)\n*[[Ambrose Puttmann]] (1910)\n*[[Crazy Schmit]] (1896)\n*[[Al Schweitzer]] (1923)\n*[[Otis Stocksdale]] (1896)\n*[[Mike Trost]] 1894)\n*[[Bob Unglaub]] (1895)\n*[[Bob Vail]] (1910)\n*[[Johnny Vander Meer]] (1954, MGR) [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame and Museum|Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Polly Wolfe]] (1921)\n*[[Bill Wynne (baseball)|Bill Wynne]] (1894)\n*[[Harley Young]] (1920)\n*[[Elmer Yoter]] (1923)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg,_VA Baseball Reference]\n\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Petersburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Professional baseball teams in Virginia]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Colonial Heights, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n| name = Petersburg Goobers\n| firstseason = 1885\n| lastseason = 1954\n| allyears =  1885\u20131886, 1894\u20131896, 1900, 1910-1921, 1923\u20131924, 1926\u20131928, 1941\u20131942, 1948\u20131951, 1954\n| city = Petersburg, Virginia\n| logo = \n| caplogo = \n| past class level ={{plainlist|\n*Class B (1895, 1920-1921, 1923\u20131924, 1926\u20131928)\n*Class C 1910\u20131919, 1941\u20131942 )\n*Class D (1900,  1923\u20131925, 1948\u20131951, 1954)\n}}\n| league =\n| conference = \n| division = \n| past league = {{plainlist|\n* [[Virginia League (1894\u201396)|Virginia League]] (1885\u20131886, 1894\u20131896)\n* [[Virginia League (1900)|Virginia League]] (1900)\n* [[Virginia League]] (1910\u20131921, 1923\u20131924, 1926\u20131928)\n* [[Virginia League (1939\u201342)|Virginia League]] (1941\u20131942)\n* [[Virginia League (1948\u201351)|Virginia League]] (1948\u20131951)\n* [[Piedmont League]] (1954)\n}}\n| pastnames = {{plainlist|\n*Petersburg (1885\u20131886)\n* Petersburg Farmers (1894\u20131896, 1900)\n* '''Petersburg Goobers''' (1910\u20131921, 1924)\n* Petersburg Trunkmakers (1923)\n* Petersburg Broncos (1926\u20131928)\n* Petersburg Rebels (1941\u20131942)\n* Petersburg Generals (1948\u20131950)\n* Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals (1951)\n* Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts (1954)\n}}\n| pastparks = {{plainlist|\n* Petersburg Ballfield (1885\u20131886, 1894\u20131896, 1900)\n* Parkinson Park (1910\u20131913)\n* McKenzie Street Park (1914, 1923\u20131925, 1948\u20131950)\n* Sherwood Park (1951, 1954) \n}}\n| pastmajorleague ={{plainlist|\n*[[St. Louis Cardinals]] (1923)\n*[[Cincinnati Reds]] (1954)\n}}\n| classchamps = \n| leaguechamps = '''5''' 1894, 1911, 1913, 1919, 1949\n| conferencechamps =  1941, 1951\n| divisionchamps = \n}}\nThe '''Petersburg Goobers''' was a primary name of the [[minor league baseball]] team representing [[Petersburg, Virginia]] from 1910\u20131921 and 1924. The Petersburg Goobers played in the [[Virginia League]]. Numerous Petersburg teams played in the Virginia League, beginning in 1885 and ending in 1951. Petersburg was a member of the 1954 [[Piedmont League]].\n\nPetersburg was an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] (1923) and [[Cincinnati Reds]] (1954).\n\n[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] member [[Sam Rice]] played for the 1914\u20131915 Petersburg Goobers.\n\n==History==\nMinor league baseball began in Petersburg in 1885, when Petersburg joined the [[Virginia League (1894\u201396)|Virginia League]]. Petersburg played in the Virginia League in 1885 and 1886.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg,_VA|title=Petersburg, VA - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Petersburg Farmers''' rejoined the six-team 1894 Virginia League, winning the 1894 Championship. The Petersburg Farmers finished 72-44 in the regular season to capture the title, as there were no league playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pf13738/y-1894|title=1894 Petersburg Farmers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-VIRL/y-1894|title=1894 Virginia League (VL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter finishing  55-69 (5th) in 1895, the Petersburg Farmers started 1896 with a 32\u201360 record. On August 13, 1896, the Petersburg Farmers moved to [[Hampton, Virginia]] to become the Hampton-Newport News Clamdiggers for the remainder of the season. The Virginia League folded after the 1896 season.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Virginia_League|title=Virginia League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pf13738/y-1896|title=1896 Petersburg Farmers/Hampton-Newport News Clamdiggers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref> Hampton-Newport News Clamdiggers\n\nThe Virginia League reformed in 1900, before folding after the season. The Petersburg Farmers were 8\u201326 when the team disbanded on June 11, 1900.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pf13738/y-1900|title=1900 Petersburg Farmers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Petersburg Goobers''' began play in the Virginia League in 1910, when the [[Portsmouth Truckers]] moved to Petersburg on July 5, 1910. The team finished 6th with a 43\u201368 record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Portsmouth_(VA)_Truckers|title=Portsmouth (VA) Truckers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-pt13898|title=Portsmouth Truckers Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Petersburg Goobers won the 1911 Virginia League Championship. Petersburg, also going by the \"Hustlers\" monkier in 1911, finished 1st at 68\u201351 to capture the championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-ph13742/y-1911|title=1911 Petersburg Hustlers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe Goobers finished 2nd in the 1912 Virginia League with a 79\u201354 record. The 1913 Petersburg Goobers captured the Virginia League Championship with their 1st place finish and 89\u201346 record.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1912|title=1912 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1913|title=1913 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1914 Petersburg Goobers finished 5th at 60\u201374. In 1915 they were 6th at 40\u201384 in the Virginia League.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Goobers|title=Petersburg Goobers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] member [[Sam Rice]] played for the Petersburg Goobers in 1914-1915. His performance in 1914, while on furlough from the [[U.S. Navy]], led Petersburg owner Dr. D.H Leigh to reach out to Virginia Senators [[Thomas S. Martin]] and [[Claude A. Swanson]] and inquire about getting Rice discharged from the Navy. In 1912, Rice was in the preseason, playing for the [[Galesburg Pavers]] when his wife, two children, his parents and two sisters were killed in a tornado. Rice eventually quit baseball and enrolled in the Navy. In 1914, with the senators help, Rice was honorably discharged from the Navy. He pitched and played the outfield for Petersburg for the remainder of the 1914 season, when he had a 9-2 record and hit .310. Rice rejoined the Petersburg Goobers for the 1915 season. On July 28, 1915, [[History of the Washington Senators (1901\u20131960)|Washington Senators]] owner [[Clark Griffith]] purchased Rice from Leigh and Petersburg. Rice was in the major leagues the next day at age 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/593ed95f|title=Sam Rice &#124; Society for American Baseball Research|website=sabr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi|title=1914 Petersburg Goobers Statistics|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1916 Petersburg Goobers finished 54\u201368, 4th in the Virginia League.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nIn 1917, the Goobers were 6\u20138 when the Virginia League disbanded on May 15, 1917.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1917|title=1917 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe Virginia League disbanded again in mid-season in 1918. The Petersburg Goobers were 27\u201322 when the league disbanded in June, 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1918|title=1918 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe Petersburg Goobers captured the 1919 Virginia League Championship. The Goobers finished 1st in the regular season with a 62\u201347 record. The Virginia League had planned to hold playoffs, but disagreements led to the playoffs being cancelled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1919|title=1919 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAfter finishing 3rd in 1920, with a 68\u201350 record, Petersburg relocated in mid-season of 1921. The Petersburg Goobers moved to [[Tarboro, North Carolina]] on August 2, 1921 after the franchise was forfeited, playing as the '''Tarboro Tarbabies'''. The 1921 Petersburg/Tarboro squad finished last with a 46\u201388 record.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi|title=1921 Petersburg Goobers/Tarboro Tarbabies Statistics|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nPetersburg returned to the Virginia League in 1923 as the '''Petersburg Trunkmakers''', an affiliate of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. The Trucnkmakers finished 6th in the six-team league with a 43\u201381 record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Trunkmakers|title=Petersburg Trunkmakers - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Petersburg Goobers moniker reappeared in 1924. The Goobers finished 46\u201389, last in the Virginia League. Petersburg folded after the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13741/y-1924|title=1924 Petersburg Goobers Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe '''Petersburg Broncos''' rejoined the Virginia League in 1926. The Broncos finished 6th (66\u201387) and 2nd (72\u201361). On June 3, 1928, the Broncos were in 3rd place with a 15\u201327 record, when the Virginia League disbanded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Broncos|title=Petersburg Broncos - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe 1941 '''Petersburg Rebels''' returned to the Virginia League. The 1941 Rebels finished 66\u201353, 1st in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Lynchburg Senators swept the Petersburg Rebels 3 games to 0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pr13743/y-1941|title=1941 Petersburg Rebels Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Petersburrg Rebels finished 3rd (74\u201352) in 1941. The Virginia League suspended play after the 1941 season due to [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pr13743/y-1942|title=1942 Petersburg Rebels Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nAfter World War II, the '''Petersburg Generals''' joined the reformed Virginia League in 1948 and advanced to the 1948 league finals. The Generals finished 73\u201362, 4th in the regular season. In the playoffs, Petersburg defeated the Suffolk Goobers 4 games to 2 and advanced. In the Finals, the Blackstone Barristers defeated the Petersburg Generals 4 games to 3. The 1948 attendance was 116,062.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13740/y-1948|title=1948 Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1949 Petersburg Generals won the Virginia League Championship. Petersburg finished 72\u201354, 2nd in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Petersburg Generals defeated the Emporia Nationals 4 games to 3. In the Finals, the Petersburg Generals  defeated the Franklin Kildees 4 games to 2 to win the cha,pionship. The 1949 season attendance was 76,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13740/y-1949|title=1949 Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg_Generals|title=Petersburg Generals - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1950, the Petersburg Generals returned to the Virginia League finals for the third consecutive season. The Generals finished 69\u201361, 2nd in the Virginia League regular season. In the playoffs, the Generals defeated the Elizabeth City Albemarles 4 games to 2. In the Finals, the Emporia Nationals defeated the Petersburg Generals 4 games to 2. The Petersburg season attendance was 43,508.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-pg13740/y-1950|title=1950 Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1951, Petersburg merged with neighboring [[Colonial Heights, Virginia]]. The team moved to play home games at Shepherd Park in Colonial Heights. The '''Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals''' advanced to the 1951 Virginia League finals. The Generals finished 80\u201339, 1st in the regular season. In the playoffs, the Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals defeated the Suffolk Goobers 4 games to 1. In the Finals, the Elizabeth City Albemarles defeated Colonial Heights-Petersburg 4 games to 1. The 1951 season attendance was 35,146. The Virginia League permanently folded after the 1951 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-VIRL5/y-1951|title=1951 Virginia League (VL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cg11000/y-1951|title=1951 Colonial Heights-Petersburg Generals Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nIn 1954, the '''Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts''' played in the [[Piedmont League]] as an affiliate of the [[Cincinnati Reds]]. The team finished  62\u201378, tied for last in the Piedmont League. The team folded after the 1954 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-cc10999|title=Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Colonial_Heights-Petersburg_Colts|title=Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Piedmont_League|title=Piedmont League - BR Bullpen|website=www.baseball-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the Colonial Heights-Petersburg Colts were succeeded in Petersburg by the [[Petersburg Generals]]. Reusing the previous moniker, the Generals became members of the [[Coastal Plain League]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==The ballparks==\nUntil 1900, Petersburg played at '''Petersburg Ballfield'''. The ballpark was located at the corner of West Washington (US 460 & US 1) & West Street, Petersburg, Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-2089|title=Petersburg Ballfield in Petersburg, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nPetersburg teams from 1910-1913 played at '''Parkinson Park'''. The ballpark was located on Canal Street, Petersburg, Virginia, near the [[Appomattox River]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-2090|title=Parkinson Park in Petersburg, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1914 to 1950, Petersburg played at '''McKenzie Street Park'''. McKenzie Street Park was located on McKenzie Street between North West Street & North Dunlop Street, Petersburg, Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-2091|title=McKenzie Street Park in Petersburg, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 1951 and 1954, Colonial Heights-Petersburg played at '''Shepherd Park'''. Today, the Shepherd Stadium Baseball Complex is still in use. The address is 901 Meridian Avenue, Colonial Heights, Virginia 23834.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/venues/v-583|title=Shepherd Stadium in Colonial Heights, VA history and teams on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.virginia.org/listings/SportsVirginia/ShepherdStadiumBaseballComplex/|title=Shepherd Stadium Baseball Complex - Virginia Is For Lovers|website=www.virginia.org}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n===[[Baseball Hall of Fame]] alumni===\n*[[Sam Rice]] (1914\u20131915) Inducted 1963\n===Notable alumni===\n*[[Ken Ash]] (1926\u20131927)\n*[[Everett Booe]] (1910\u20131912)\n*[[Dick Burrus]] (1917)\n*[[Tommy Clarke]] (1920, MGR)\n*[[Guy Cooper]] (1913)\n*[[Art Corcoran]] (1921) NFL MLB player\n*[[Harry Damrau]] (1913\u20131914)\n*[[Harley Dillinger]] (1917)\n*[[Davey Dunkle]] (1895)\n*[[Gus Dundon]] (1896)\n*[[John Farrell (second baseman)|John Farrell]] (1894)\n*[[Brownie Foreman]] (1894\u20131895)\n*[[Bill Gardner (baseball)|Bill Gardner]] (1886)\n*[[Jimmy Grant]] (1948)\n*[[June Greene]] (1923)\n*[[Bill Hallman]] (1896)\n*[[Harry Hedgpeth]] (1912\u20131914)\n*[[Snake Henry]] (1916)\n*[[Izzy Hoffman]] (1900)\n*[[Jack Horner (baseball)|Jack Horner]] (1894)\n*[[Bill Jackson (first baseman)|Bill Jackson]] (1910)\n*[[Vic Keen]] (1918)\n*[[Mickey Keliher]] (1910\u20131911, 1915)\n*[[Enos Kirkpatrick]] (1910)\n*[[Frank Kitson (baseball)|Frank Kitson]] (1896)\n*[[Ed Konetchy]] (1924, MGR)\n*[[Tommy Leach]] (1896)\n*[[Doc McJames]] (1894\u20131895)\n*[[Billy Martin (shortstop)|Bill Martin]] (1921, MGR)\n*[[Amby McConnell]] (1919\u20131921) (1919, 1921, MGR)\n*[[Herm McFarland]] (1910)\n*[[Doc McJames]] (1895)\n*[[Rufus Meadows]] (1924)\n*[[George Mohart]] (1916)\n*[[Greg Mulleavy]] (1927)\n*[[Bert Myers]] (1894)\n*[[Vance Page]] (1928)\n*[[Dixie Parker]] (1918\u20131919)\n*[[Ed Porray]] (1915)\n*[[Doc Powers]] (1896)\n*[[Ambrose Puttmann]] (1910)\n*[[Crazy Schmit]] (1896)\n*[[Al Schweitzer]] (1923)\n*[[Otis Stocksdale]] (1896)\n*[[Mike Trost]] 1894)\n*[[Bob Unglaub]] (1895)\n*[[Bob Vail]] (1910)\n*[[Johnny Vander Meer]] (1954, MGR) [[Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame and Museum|Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Polly Wolfe]] (1921)\n*[[Bill Wynne (baseball)|Bill Wynne]] (1894)\n*[[Harley Young]] (1920)\n*[[Elmer Yoter]] (1923)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Petersburg,_VA Baseball Reference]\n\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Petersburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Professional baseball teams in Virginia]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals minor league affiliates]]\n[[Category:Colonial Heights, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Skilgis1900", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petersburg_Goobers"}
{"title_page": "Mike Will Made It", "text_new": "{{short description|American record producer and DJ}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Mike Will Made It\n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Michael Len Williams II\n| alias            = Mike Will\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1989|3|23}}\n| birth_place      = [[Marietta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Atlanta]], Georgia, U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]|[[Pop music|pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Record producer|[[DJ]]|rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Korg Triton|Akai MPC 1000|Logic Pro|FL Studio|Yamaha Motif|Roland Fantom-X.|vocals}}\n| years_active     = 2005\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|EarDrummers|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}} \n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Rae Sremmurd]]|[[Future (rapper)|Future]]|[[Gucci Mane]]|[[Juicy J]]|[[Miley Cyrus]]|[[Rock City (duo)|Rock City]]|[[Trouble (rapper)|Trouble]]|[[Yo Gotti]] | [[Kendrick Lamar]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|mikewillmade.it}}\n}}\n'''Michael Len Williams II''' (born March 23, 1989), known professionally as '''Mike Will Made It''' (often stylized as '''Mike WiLL Made-It''')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/5747924/mike-will-made-it|title=Mike Will Made-It|publisher=|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> or simply '''Mike Will''', is an American record producer, DJ, rapper, singer and songwriter. He is best known for [[Hip hop production|producing]] [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap beats]] for several [[Southern hip hop]] artists as well as for producing several singles, such as \"[[Black Beatles]]\" and \"[[Powerglide (song)|Powerglide]]\" by [[Rae Sremmurd]], \"[[Mercy (GOOD Music song)|Mercy]]\" by [[GOOD Music]], \"[[No Lie (2 Chainz song)|No Lie]]\" by [[2 Chainz]], \"[[Bandz a Make Her Dance]]\" by [[Juicy J]], \"[[Pour It Up]]\" by [[Rihanna]], \"[[Love Me (Lil Wayne song)|Love Me]]\" by [[Lil Wayne]], \"[[Body Party]]\" by [[Ciara]], \"[[We Can't Stop]]\" by [[Miley Cyrus]], \"[[Formation (song)|Formation]]\" by [[Beyonc\u00e9]], and \"[[Humble (song)|Humble]]\" by [[Kendrick Lamar]]. He has released six [[mixtape]]s and one studio album, ''[[Ransom 2]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nWilliams Gay Ass, was born in [[Marietta, Georgia]], the youngest of three children; he has two older sisters.<ref name=faderconstruction>{{cite web|last=Noz|first=Andrew|title=Beat Construction: Mike WiLL Made It|url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/04/30/beat-construction-mike-will-made-it/|publisher=The Fader|date=April 30, 2012}}</ref> His father, Michael Williams Sr., is a former [[IBM]] executive who worked as a club DJ in the 1970s. His mother,  Shirley Williams, a prostitute former bank loan officer, was once in a gospel group, singing for [[Dottie Peoples]]. He grew up in a musical family as his uncle was an accomplished guitar player and one of his older sisters was a drum major in the Olympics.<ref name=faderconstruction /> While growing up, Mike Will was athletic, participating in a number of sports, including basketball, baseball, and football, with dreams of becoming a professional athlete.<ref name=complex3-5>{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Julian|title=Beyond the Beats: Mike WiLL|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/03/behind-the-boards-mike-will/|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=March 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis life also centered around a love of hip hop music and sex. Mike Will first developed his talent for music by re-playing popular instrumentals that he heard on the radio while he and his friends would [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] to them.<ref name=faderconstruction /> In a number of interviews, Will has mentioned, in particular, re-playing the instrumental for \"[[Still Fly]]\", a popular song by the southern rap group [[Big Tymers]], on a [[Casio]] brand keyboard, and has also mentioned re-playing \"[[Young'n (Holla Back)]]\" by New York rapper [[Fabolous]] on production equipment at a local music store.<ref name=hhtobias>{{cite web|last=Tobias|first=Jonathan|title=Mike Will Made It Explains Convincing Young Jeezy Of A \"TM103\" Track, Working With Gucci Mane As A Teenager|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/dxnext/id.226/title.mike-will-made-it-explains-convincing-young-jeezy-of-a-tm103-track-working-with-gucci-mane-as-a-teenager|publisher=Hip Hop DX|date=December 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt age 14, Mike Will began to develop his own beats on a [[Korg]] ES1 beat machine, which his father bought for him as a Christmas present from the local music store [[Mars Music]]. As Mike Will became more accomplished, he also began to use production equipment, including the Korg Triton, the Akai MPC1000, the [[Yamaha Motif]], and the Roland Fantom.<ref name=faderconstruction /> By the time Mike Will was 16, he was spending time at local recording studios in Atlanta, trying to shop his beats to established artists.<ref name=\"Devin Leonard\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-08-07/mike-will-made-it-hip-hops-hottest-producer-is-crossover-king | title=Hip-Hop Producer Mike WiLL's Makeover of Miley Cyrus Was Only the Beginning | date=August 7, 2014 | accessdate=16 March 2016 | author=Devin Leonard}}</ref> He was initially ignored, but eventually one of his beat tapes made its way into the hands of [[Gucci Mane]], who then invited Mike Will to Patchwerk studios, an Atlanta recording studio.<ref name=\"Devin Leonard\"/>\n\nUpon graduating high school, Mike Will enrolled at [[Georgia State University]] to pursue undergraduate studies mainly due to pressure from his parents, but chose to take a hiatus and eventually dropped out after several semesters,  with a 3.1 GPA, to focus on his music career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2012/04/30/beat-construction-mike-will-made-it/|title=Beat Construction: Mike Will Made It|work=The FADER|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en}}</ref> During this hiatus, he produced his first hit. Upon hearing one of his produced singles \"[[Tupac Back]]\" began to enjoy success on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' rap and Hot 100 charts, Mike Will decided to quit school and focus on his music career full-time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://theburtonwire.com/2015/02/23/entertainment/mike-will-made-it-debuts-ear-drummers-act-rae-sremmurd/ | title=Mike WiLL Made-It Debuts Ear Drummers\u2019 Act Rae Sremmurd | publisher=The Burton Wire | date=February 23, 2015 | accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> He has since advised aspiring music producers not to drop out of college if they are not sure of their own future career outcome or lacking a defined plan before entering the industry.<ref name=faderconstruction />\n\n==Career==\n{{outdated section|date=December 2017}}\n\n===2011\u20132012: Production and mixtapes===\n\nIn an interview with ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'', Mike Will said, \"Gucci Mane was the first [major artist] to ever [[Rapping|rap]] on my beat.\"<ref name=xxlbristout>{{cite web|last=Bristout|first=Ralph|title=Production Credit: Mike Will Speaks on Working With Rick Ross, Young Jeezy & 50 Cent|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/features/2012/01/mike-will-speaks-on-working-with-rick-ross-young-jeezy-50-cent-production-credit/|publisher=XXL Magazine|date=January 26, 2012}}</ref>  Mike Will first met Gucci Mane at Atlanta recording studio, [[PatchWerk Recording Studios]], and upon introducing himself and giving Gucci Mane a CD of beats, Gucci Mane proceeded to [[freestyle rap|freestyle]] over each of the instrumentals.<ref name=boombox>{{cite web|last=Graham|first=-made-it-producer/|date=February 22, 2012}}</ref> He then offered Mike Will $1,000 for one of his beats.<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5645388/mike-will-made-it-the-billboard-cover-story |title=Mike Will Made It: The Billboard Cover Story |publisher=Billboard |date=2013-08-09 |accessdate=2013-10-16}}</ref> The two artists began releasing songs together, such as \"East Atlanta 6\", and a number of songs from Gucci Mane's mixtape, ''No Pad, No Pencil''.<ref name=boombox /> After developing this close relationship with Gucci Mane, he began working with other big-name Atlanta rappers such as [[Future (rapper)|Future]], [[Waka Flocka Flame]], [[Rocko (rapper)|Rocko]], and 2 Chainz.<ref name=\"billboard1\"/>\n\nIn 2011, Mike Will released his first [[Single (music)|single]], \"[[Tupac Back]]\", performed by [[Meek Mill]] and [[Rick Ross]], from the compilation album ''[[Self Made Vol. 1]]''.<ref name=complextupac>{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Julian|title=Beyond the Beats: Mike WiLL|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/03/behind-the-boards-mike-will/meek-mill-tupac-back|date=March 5, 2012}}</ref> The single was released on April 5, 2011 and peaked at #31 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=R&B/Hip Hop Songs|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2011-07-09/r-b-hip-hop-songs?order=drop|publisher=Billboard Magazine|date=July 9, 2011}}</ref> This came after Mike Will submitted some of his beats to an A&R for Rick Ross' [[Maybach Music Group]] label.<ref name=complextupac />\n\nAlso in 2011, Mike Will worked with Atlanta rapper Future, producing several popular and noteworthy songs together, including \"[[Ain't No Way Around It (DJ Drama song)|Ain't No Way Around It]]\",<ref name=complexfuture>{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Julian|title=Beyond the Beats: Mike WiLL|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/03/behind-the-boards-mike-will/future-aint-no-way-around-it|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=March 5, 2012}}</ref> \"Itchin\", and three songs from Future's 2012 major label debut album ''[[Pluto (Future album)|Pluto]]'': \"Neva End\", \"Truth Gonna Hurt You\", and \"[[Turn On the Lights (song)|Turn On the Lights]]\".<ref name=faderconstruction /> \"Turn On the Lights\" was promoted as a single, and to date has peaked at #2 on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs ''Billboard chart''.<ref name=billboardfuture>{{cite web|title=R&B/Hip Hop Songs|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-09-29/r-b-hip-hop-songs|publisher=Billboard Magazine|date=September 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn December 27, 2011, Mike Will released his first mixtape, ''Est. in 1989 (Last of a Dying Breed)''.<ref name=lmtpart1>{{cite web|title=Mike Will - Est. In 1989 (Last Of A Dying Breed)|url=http://www.livemixtapes.com/mixtapes/14265/mike_will_est_in_1989.html|publisher=Live Mixtapes|date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> It was released in conjunction with popular mixtape website LiveMixtapes.com.<ref name=lmtpart1 /> ''Est. in 1989'' includes a mix of exclusive songs and songs from Mike Will's catalog, and features artists such as Gucci Mane & [[1017 Brick Squad]], Future, [[Waka Flocka Flame]], [[Kanye West]] & [[GOOD Music]], 2 Chainz, [[Lil Boosie]], [[Ludacris]], [[Lil Wayne]].<ref name=complexestmt>{{cite web|last=Moore|first=Jacob|title=Mixtape: Mike WiLL Made-It \"Est. In 1989\"|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/12/mixtape-mike-will-made-it-est-in-1989-last-of-a-dying-breed|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=December 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, 2012, Mike Will partnered with popular music site [[The Fader|The FADER]] to announce the second installment of his mixtape series, ''Est. in 1989 Pt. 2'', and to release the mixtape's first single, \"Back 2 the Basics\", which features his manager/rapper Gucci Mane, founder/CEO/president of Brick Squad and Waka Flocka Flame.<ref name=faderbasics>{{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Duncan|title=Gucci Mane and Waka Flocka Flame, \"Back 2 The Basics\" (Prod. by Mike WiLL Made-It) MP3|url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/03/23/gucci-mane-and-waka-flocka-back-2-basics-prod-by-mike-will-mp3/|publisher=Fader Magazine|date=March 23, 2012}}</ref> The project ''Est. in 1989 Pt. 2'' features songs with [[Sean Combs|Diddy]], 2 Chainz, Juicy J, Future, Lil Wayne, [[T.I.]], [[Mac Miller]], [[French Montana]], [[Jeremih]], and others.<ref name=faderestp2 /> The album was released again on July 24, 2012 in partnership with LiveMixtapes.com.<ref name=faderestp2>{{cite web|last=Zeichner|first=Naomi|title=Download Mike Will Made It\u2019s Est. In 1989 (Part 2) Mixtape|url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/07/24/download-mike-will-made-its-est-in-1989-part-2-mixtape/|publisher=The Fader|date=July 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWill has also worked extensively with Atlanta rapper 2 Chainz, producing \"La La\", which features [[Busta Rhymes]], from 2 Chainz, then known as [[Tity Boi]], ''Codeine Cowboy'' mixtape and \"Got One\" from 2 Chainz's ''[[T.R.U. REALigion]]'' mixtape.<ref>{{cite web|title=Audio: Tity Boi Ft. Busta Rhymes \u2013 Lala [Prod. By Mike WiLL Made-It] (NO DJ)|url=http://www.dirtyglovebastard.net/?p=33694|publisher=Dirty Glove Bastard|date=February 23, 2012}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=complexgotone>{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Julian|title=Beyond the Beat: Mike Will|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/03/behind-the-boards-mike-will/2-chainz-got-one|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=March 5, 2012}}</ref> According to an interview with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' magazine, Mike Will has been working together with 2 Chainz \"since 2008, when he was [[Tity Boi]]...We're kind of like family.\"<ref name=complexchainzdrake>{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Julian|title=Interview: Mike Will On Producing 2 Chainz & Drake's \"No Lie\"|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/05/interview-mike-will-on-producing-2-chainz-drakes-no-lie|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=May 4, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, Mike Will produced the lead single, \"[[No Lie (2 Chainz song)|No Lie]]\", from 2 Chainz' debut album, ''[[Based on a T.R.U. Story]]'', released via [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]].<ref name=complexchainzdrake /> The single, which features popular recording artist [[Drake (entertainer)|Drake]], was released May 8, 2012, and debuted in the top 50 of the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], ultimately peaking at #1 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=R&B/Hip Hop Songs|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-09-15/r-b-hip-hop-songs|publisher=Billboard Magazine|date=September 15, 2012}}</ref> The single has been certified [[RIAA certification|Gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], selling over 500,000 copies digitally.<ref name=hhdxnolie>{{cite web|last=Horowitz|first=Steven J.|title=2 Chainz's \"No Lie\" Certified Gold|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.20560/title.2-chainzs-no-lie-certified-gold|publisher=Hip Hop DX|date=July 26, 2012|access-date=September 25, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403010155/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.20560/title.2-chainzs-no-lie-certified-gold|archive-date=April 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Mike WiLL Made-It produced \"[[Bandz a Make Her Dance]]\", a single for [[Taylor Gang Records|Taylor Gang]] rapper Juicy J that also features Lil Wayne and 2 Chainz.<ref>{{cite web|title=Juicy J \u2013 Bands A Make Her Dance (rmx) f. Lil Wayne & 2 Chainz|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/06/18/juicy-j-bands-a-make-her-dance-rmx-f-lil-wayne-2-chainz/|publisher=2 Dope Boyz|date=June 18, 2012}}</ref> The song was listed as one of the 25 Best Songs of Summer 2012 by ''Complex'' magazine, and as of September 2012, the single had peaked at #14 on the ''Billboard'' Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 25 Best Songs of Summer 2012|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/08/the-25-best-songs-of-summer-2012/juicy-j-bands-a-make-her-dance|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=August 16, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=R&B/Hip Hop Songs|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-09-29/r-b-hip-hop-songs?begin=11&order=position|publisher=Billboard Magazine|date=September 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMike Will, alongside producers Kanye West, [[Mike Dean (producer)|Mike Dean]], Lifted, and Anthony Kilhoffer, co-produced the [[G.O.O.D. Music]] single \"[[Mercy (Kanye West song)|Mercy]]\", which features vocals by Kanye West, [[Big Sean]], 2 Chainz, and [[Pusha T]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The 25 Best Songs of Summer 2012|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/08/the-25-best-songs-of-summer-2012/good-music-mercy|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=August 16, 2012}}</ref> \"[[Mercy (Kanye West song)|Mercy]]\", released April 3, 2012, served as the lead single from the G.O.O.D. Music compilation album ''[[Cruel Summer (GOOD Music album)|Cruel Summer]]'', and peaked at #1 on the ''Billboard'' Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart, while reaching #13 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hot 100|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=kanye west|chart=Hot 100}}|publisher=Billboard Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hot 100|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=kanye west|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Songs}}|publisher=Billboard Magazine}}</ref> Other notable production efforts for Mike Will include the single \"Way Too Gone\", featuring Future from [[Young Jeezy]]'s 2011 studio album ''[[Thug Motivation 103: Hustlerz Ambition]]'', \"Just a Sign\" from [[B.o.B]]'s second studio album ''[[Strange Clouds (album)|Strange Clouds]]'' and \"[[Pour It Up]]\" from [[Rihanna]]'s 2012 studio album, ''[[Unapologetic]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Julian|title=Beyond the Beats: Mike WiLL|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/03/behind-the-boards-mike-will/young-jeezy-f-future-way-too-gone|date=March 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=B.o.B. Speaks on Mike WiLL Made-It's Est. in 1989 Pt.2 p(Video)|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/07/16/b-o-b-speaks-on-mike-will-made-its-est-in-1989-pt-2-video/|publisher=2 Dope Boyz|date=July 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 interviews, Mike Will mentioned upcoming work with Kanye West, [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]], Big Sean, and Pusha T.<ref name=complexchainzdrake />\n\nThe third installment of the series, entitled ''Est. in 1989 2.5'' was released on December 24, 2012.<ref name=2DBwill>{{cite web|first=Meka|title=Mike WiLL Made It \u2013 Est In 1989 2.5 (Mixtape)|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2012/12/24/mike-will-made-it-est-in-1989-2-5-mixtape/|publisher=2 Dope Boyz|date=December 24, 2012|author=Meka}}</ref>  The mixtape featured guest appearances from Gucci Mane, Future, [[Rihanna]], Big Sean, [[Trinidad Jame$]], Lil Wayne, and other artists.<ref>{{cite web | title = Mike WiLL Made It \"Est. In 1989 2.5\" Mixtape Cover Art & Release Date | url = http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22054/title.mike-will-made-it-est-in-1989-25-mixtape-cover-art-release-date | publisher = HipHop DX | date =  | accessdate = 1 December 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150403184847/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22054/title.mike-will-made-it-est-in-1989-25-mixtape-cover-art-release-date | archive-date = 3 April 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n===2013\u2013present: Debut studio album and Miley Cyrus collaborations===\nMike Will executive produced Miley Cyrus's fourth studio album ''[[Bangerz]]'' (2013), including its lead single \"[[We Can't Stop]]\".  He produced eight tracks on ''Bangerz'' and six tracks on ''Miley Cyrus & Her Dead Petz''.\n\nOn September 9, 2013, Mike Will premiered his commercial d\u00e9but single \"[[23 (song)|23]]\", featuring [[Wiz Khalifa]], Juicy J and Miley Cyrus. He revealed that he had signed with [[Interscope Records]] to release his debut album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/mike-will-made-it-f-miley-cyrus-wif-khalifa-juicy-j-23 |title=Mike WiLL Made It, Miley Cyrus, Wiz Khalifa, Juicy J \"23\" |publisher=Complex |date=2013-09-09 |accessdate=2013-10-16}}</ref> His debut album will also feature Beyonc\u00e9, Future, [[Kendrick Lamar]], and 2 Chainz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/video-mike-will-made-it-f-miley-cyrus-wiz-khalifa-juicy-j-23 |title=Mike WiLL Made It f/ Miley Cyrus, Wiz Khalifa & Juicy J \"23\" Video |publisher=Complex |date=2013-09-24 |accessdate=2013-10-16}}</ref>\n\nHe was named producer of the year by [[HipHopDX]] on December 18, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/editorials/id.2241/title.the-2013-hiphopdx-year-end-awards|title=The 2013 HipHopDX Year End Awards|first=HipHopDX -|last=http://hiphopdx.com|publisher=|accessdate=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122060241/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/editorials/id.2241/title.the-2013-hiphopdx-year-end-awards|archive-date=22 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn June 17, 2014, Mike WIll Made It released the first single from his upcoming mixtape, \"Buy the World\", featuring [[Future (rapper)|Future]], Lil Wayne and Kendrick Lamar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/buy-world-feat.-future-lil/id888908768|title=Buy the World (feat. Lil Wayne, Kendrick Lamar & Future) - Single by Mike Will Made-It on iTunes|publisher=|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> On December 15, 2014, he released his fifth mixtape, ''Ransom''. Featured artists include Big Sean, Juicy J, 2 Chainz, Lil Wayne and Kendrick Lamar.\n\nOn March 24, 2017, he released ''Ransom 2''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7727761/mike-will-made-it-ransom-2-release-date|title=Mike Will Made-It Reveals 'Ransom 2' Release Date|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-01-04}}</ref> The bigger names showcase a quick flip through Mike WiLL\u2019s contact list: Rihanna, Kendrick Lamar, Future, Pharrell, Lil Wayne, Big Sean, Migos, YG, and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/23087-ransom-2/|title=Mike WiLL Made-It: Ransom 2 Album Review {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nIn interviews, Mike Will has named a number of musical influences on his own production work. In a \"Behind the Beats\" interview with ''Complex'' magazine, he says that he \"always admired [[Dr. Dre]]'s drums\", and calls [[Timbaland]] \"the first crazy pop producer... He brought so many artists to the game.\"<ref name=complexinfl>{{cite web|last=Pereira|first=Julian|title=Beyond the Beats: Mike WiLL|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/03/behind-the-boards-mike-will/influences|publisher=Complex Magazine|date=March 5, 2012}}</ref> As a southern producer, he says, he \"was also looking up to [[Shawty Redd]]. He was the first producer to really bring that dark trap energy and sound.\"<ref name=complexinfl /> He also refers to [[DJ Toomp]] as \"my big brother or my mentor\", saying, \"I love what he does.\"<ref name=complexinfl /> In an interview, with [[AOL]]'s The Boombox, Mike WiLL also cites [[Pharrell Williams|Pharrell]] as a producer that he respects.<ref name=boombox />\n\n==Production equipment==\nMike Will uses a variety of production equipment to create beats. His gear includes the Korg Triton, Akai MPC 1000, [[Logic Pro]], [[FL Studio]], [[Yamaha Motif]], and the [[Roland Fantom-X]].<ref name=faderconstruction /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/12/12/drum-majors-four-producers-to-watch | title=Drum Majors: Four Producers to Watch | publisher=The Fader | date=12 December 2012 | accessdate=10 March 2015 |author1=Matthew Schnipper |author2=Naomi Zeichner |author3=JORDAN SARGENT |author4=Olivia Graham }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://v103.cbslocal.com/2012/01/31/producers-week-day-2-mike-will-made-it-and-m-sixteen/ | title=\"Producers Week\" Day 2: Mike Will Made It And M-Sixteen! | publisher=V-103 | date=January 31, 2012 | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Ear Drummer Records==\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name        = Ear Drummer Records\n| image       = \n| image_size  = 174px\n| parent      = [[Universal Music Group]]\n| founded     = {{Start date and age|2013}}\n| founder     = Mike Will Made It\n| distributor = [[Interscope Records]]\n| genre       = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| location    = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| website     = {{URL|ear-drummer.com}}\n}}\n\nIn 2006, Mike Will started his own production company called {{visible anchor|EarDrummers Entertainment}}. In 2013, he founded Ear Drummer Records (initially known as Eardruma Records) and signed the label to [[Interscope Records]] on December 19, 2013.<ref name=\"xxl\">{{cite web|last1=J.|first1=Miranda|title=Mike WiLL Made It Wants To Develop A New Sound This Year|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/tags/eardruma-records/|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"hiphopdx\">{{cite web|last1=Tardio|first1=Andres|title=Mike WiLL Made-It's Eardruma Records Officially Signs With Interscope|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.26366/title.mike-will-made-its-eardruma-records-officially-signs-with-interscope|website=[[HipHopDX]]|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref> In 2014, Mike Will signed [[Rae Sremmurd]] and [[Two-9]] to the label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/mike-will-made-it-signs-two-9-to-eardruma-interscope-records-news.11472.html|title=Mike WiLL Made It Signs Two-9 To Eardruma/Interscope Records|publisher=|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/03/rae-sremmurd-no-flex-zone-prod-mike-will-made-it|title=Listen to Rae Sremmurd's Mike WiLL Made It-Produced \"No Flex Zone\"|publisher=|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Artists===\n* Mike Will Made It\n*Shotta Spence \n* [[Two-9]]\n* [[Rae Sremmurd]]\n* Eearz<ref>{{cite web|title=EarDrummers Rapper Eearz Talks Working with Mike WiLL Made-It, Announces New Project |url=https://medium.com/the-clout/eardrummers-rapper-eaarz-talks-working-with-mike-will-made-it-announces-new-project-af7918fa15fc |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* Andr\u00e9a<ref>{{cite web|title=This Mike WiLL Made-It Collaborator Is About To Drop Something Serious |url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/01/30/andrea-mike-will-made-made-it-eardrummers-video |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Trouble (rapper)|Trouble]]\n* Rico Pressley\n\n===In-house producers===\n* [[30 Roc]]<ref>{{cite web|title=HHS1987 Presents: Behind The Beats With 30 Roc |url=http://hiphopsince1987.com/2016/news/hhs1987-presents-behind-the-beats-with-30-roc/ |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* Blue Cheeze<ref name=\"instagram\">{{cite web|title=Blue Cheeze (@eardrummer_blue) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|url=https://www.instagram.com/eardrummer_blue/|website=[[Instagram]]|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n* DJ Fu<ref>{{cite web|title=Premiere: Dro Fe Grabs Maxo Kream For Some Texas Heat On \"Boom Boom\" |url=http://www.vibe.com/2016/05/dro-fe-maxo-kream-boom-boom/ |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Ducko McFli]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Firestarter :: EarDrummers' Ducko McFli on His Own Terms |url=https://thehundreds.com/blogs/content/firestarter-eardrummers-ducko-mcfli-on-his-own-terms-interview |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\"This Guy Won?\": An Interview with Producer Ducko McFli |url=http://djbooth.net/news/entry/2017-06-23-ducko-mcfli-interview |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* GT<ref>{{cite web|title=Trill Sammy - Road Runnin' Feat. Landstrip Chip |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/trill-sammy-runnin-feat-landstrip-chip-new-song.1973328.html |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* J-Bo<ref name=edebd>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Mike Will Made It Breaks Down His EarDrummers Empire |url=http://hiphopwired.com/403008/exclusive-mike-will-made-it-eardrummers-empire-video/ |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* Marz<ref name=edebd/>\n* Mike Will Made It\n* Pluss<ref name=edebd/><ref name=mnpn>{{cite web|title=Certified Fresh: Mike Will Made It Explains The Making Of \"Bandz A Make Her Dance,\" \"No Lie\" & More |url=http://hiphopwired.com/194049/certified-fresh-mike-will-made-it-explains-the-making-of-bandz-a-make-here-dance-no-lie-more-video/ |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* P-Nazty<ref name=edebd/><ref name=mnpn/>\n* Randy Lanphear\n* Resource<ref>{{cite web|title=Check Your Resources: A Conversation With Mike WiLL\u2019s Secret Weapon |url=http://djbooth.net/news/entry/2017-04-11-resource-ear-drummers-interview |accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>\n* Scooly<ref name=edebd/>\n* [[Swae Lee]]\n* Whatlilshoddysay\n* F1Jo\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Mike Will Made It production discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of albums, with selected details\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\" | Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=\"US200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/mike-will-made-it/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Mike Will Made-It Chart History: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.2em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US R&B]]<br/><ref name=\"RBHH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/mike-will-made-it/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-albums|title=Mike Will Made-It Chart History: Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.2em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Top Rap Albums|US Rap]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/5747924/Mike+Will+Made-It/chart?f=335|title=Mike Will Made-It \u2013 Chart History: Top Rap Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br><ref name=\"CANAlbums\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/mike-will-made-it/chart-history/canadian-albums|title=Mike Will Made-It \u2013 Chart History: Canadian Albums|work=Bil