{"title_page": "M\u00e9morable", "text_new": "\n\n{{Redirect|Memorable|the general concept|Memory}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = M\u00e9morable\n| image          = Poster_for_2019_film_M\u00e9morable.jpg\n| director       = Bruno Collet\n| producer       = Jean-Francois Le Corre\n| writer         = Bruno Collet\n| starring       = Dominique Reymond, Andr\u00e9 Wilms\n| music          = Nicolas Martin\n| cinematography = Fabien Drouet\n| editing        = Jean-Marie Le Rest\n| distributor    = Vivement Lundi\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2019|6|11}}\n| runtime        = 12 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n}}\n\n'''''M\u00e9morable''''' is a [[2019 in film|2019]] French short animated film written and directed by Bruno Collet. The stop-motion film deals with [[Alzheimer's disease]], and was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]].\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film concerns the relationship between Louis, a painter suffering from increasing dementia, and his wife Michelle. At first, Louis seems merely forgetful, but as the film progresses his dementia becomes apparent.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/memorable-director-bruno-collet-oscars-animated-short-interview-news-1202843947/|title='Memorable' Director Bruno Collet Uses Stop-Motion To Tap Into Aging Painter's Experience of Dementia|last=Grobar|first=Matt|date=January 28, 2020|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The viewer experiences much of this from Louis' point of view; objects melt and shape shift in his hand. When Louis encounters other characters, such as the doctor Michelle takes him to, they appear strange and monstrous.\u00a0Aware of his condition, Louis tapes notes on household objects to remind himself of their usage, but this effort ends with him sitting in a sea of detached notes. Michelle notices the effect Louis' condition has on his increasingly abstract paintings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/road-92nd-oscars-animated-short-film-nominees|title=On the Road to the 92nd Oscars: The Animated Short Film Nominees|last=McLean|first=Thomas J.|date=February 6, 2020|website=Animation World Network|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the film, Louis no longer recognizes Michelle, who appears to him now as a translucent figure made of scattered paint strokes. Still, Louis is stunned by Michelle's beauty. They dance together until Michelle dissolves into a swirl of floating dots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reanimania.com/memorable-a-story-you-can-never-forget/|title=M\u00e9morable: A story you can never forget|last=Danielyan|first=Anna|date=October 18, 2019|website=ReAnimania|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nBruno Collet was inspired to create the film when he saw the paintings of William Utermohlen, an American painter who kept working throughout his [[Alzheimer's disease]] diagnosis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/animated-people/mind-altering-french-animator-bruno-collet-discusses-his-oscar-nominated-short-memorable/|title=Mind-Altering: French Animator Bruno Collet Discusses His Oscar-Nominated Short 'Memorable'|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|date=January 20, 2020|website=Animation Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The film is primarily made with [[Stop motion|stop-motion]] animation, but [[Computer animation|computer-generated 3D]] effects are also utilized.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Accolades==\nThe film premiered at the [[Annecy International Animated Film Festival]] where it won the Cristal for a Short Film, the Audience Award, and the Junior Jury Award for a Short Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.annecy.org/festival/awards/film-index-award-winner:film-20192412|title=M\u00e9morable|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Annecy Festival|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was also nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2020|title=The 92nd Academy Awards: 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DyAhZrmsqh0 \"Hair Love\" wins Best Animated Short Film-Oscars on YouTube]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10499942/ IMDb]\n*[https://mubi.com/films/memorable MUBI]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VSV5lHZxgyI Excerpt]\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s animated films]]\n[[Category:Stop-motion animated short films]]\n[[Category:Films about memory]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too short|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Redirect|Memorable|the general concept|Memory}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = M\u00e9morable\n| image          = Poster_for_2019_film_M\u00e9morable.jpg\n| director       = Bruno Collet\n| producer       = Jean-Francois Le Corre\n| writer         = Bruno Collet\n| starring       = Dominique Reymond, Andr\u00e9 Wilms\n| music          = Nicolas Martin\n| cinematography = Fabien Drouet\n| editing        = Jean-Marie Le Rest\n| distributor    = Vivement Lundi\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2019|6|11}}\n| runtime        = 12 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n}}\n\n'''''M\u00e9morable''''' is a [[2019 in film|2019]] French short animated film written and directed by Bruno Collet.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film concerns the relationship between Louis, a painter suffering from increasing dementia, and his wife Michelle. At first, Louis seems merely forgetful, but as the film progresses his dementia becomes apparent.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/memorable-director-bruno-collet-oscars-animated-short-interview-news-1202843947/|title='Memorable' Director Bruno Collet Uses Stop-Motion To Tap Into Aging Painter's Experience of Dementia|last=Grobar|first=Matt|date=January 28, 2020|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The viewer experiences much of this from Louis' point of view; objects melt and shape shift in his hand. When Louis encounters other characters, such as the doctor Michelle takes him to, they appear strange and monstrous.\u00a0Aware of his condition, Louis tapes notes on household objects to remind himself of their usage, but this effort ends with him sitting in a sea of detached notes. Michelle notices the effect Louis' condition has on his increasingly abstract paintings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/road-92nd-oscars-animated-short-film-nominees|title=On the Road to the 92nd Oscars: The Animated Short Film Nominees|last=McLean|first=Thomas J.|date=February 6, 2020|website=Animation World Network|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the film, Louis no longer recognizes Michelle, who appears to him now as a translucent figure made of scattered paint strokes. Still, Louis is stunned by Michelle's beauty. They dance together until Michelle dissolves into a swirl of floating dots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reanimania.com/memorable-a-story-you-can-never-forget/|title=M\u00e9morable: A story you can never forget|last=Danielyan|first=Anna|date=October 18, 2019|website=ReAnimania|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nBruno Collet was inspired to create the film when he saw the paintings of William Utermohlen, an American painter who kept working throughout his [[Alzheimer's disease]] diagnosis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/animated-people/mind-altering-french-animator-bruno-collet-discusses-his-oscar-nominated-short-memorable/|title=Mind-Altering: French Animator Bruno Collet Discusses His Oscar-Nominated Short 'Memorable'|last=Zahed|first=Ramin|date=January 20, 2020|website=Animation Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The film is primarily made with [[Stop motion|stop-motion]] animation, but [[Computer animation|computer-generated 3D]] effects are also utilized.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Accolades==\nThe film premiered at the [[Annecy International Animated Film Festival]] where it won the Cristal for a Short Film, the Audience Award, and the Junior Jury Award for a Short Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.annecy.org/festival/awards/film-index-award-winner:film-20192412|title=M\u00e9morable|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Annecy Festival|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was also nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2020|title=The 92nd Academy Awards: 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DyAhZrmsqh0 \"Hair Love\" wins Best Animated Short Film-Oscars on YouTube]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10499942/ IMDb]\n*[https://mubi.com/films/memorable MUBI]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VSV5lHZxgyI Excerpt]\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s animated films]]\n[[Category:Stop-motion animated short films]]\n[[Category:Films about memory]]\n", "name_user": "KarlenP", "label": "safe", "comment": "attempted to address the \"lead to short\" feedback", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%A9morable"}
{"title_page": "Drew Gooden (comedian)", "text_new": "{{short description|American comedian and filmmaker|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{Notability|date=January 2020}}{{blp sources|date=January 2020}}{{unreliable|date=January 2020}}}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n|name              = Drew Gooden\n|image             = Drew Gooden.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           =Gooden in 2016\n|birth_name        = Drew Gooden\n|nationality       = {{ubl||American}}\n|residence         = [[KurtisTown]], U.S.\n|education         =\n|channel_url      = UCTSRIY3GLFYIpkR2QwyeklA\n|channel_display_name = Drew Gooden\n|years_active      = 2015\u2013present\n|genre             = {{hlist|[[Comedy]]|[[criticism|Commentary]]}}\n|subscribers       = 2.14 million\n|views             = 208 million\n|associated_acts   =\n|silver_button     = yes\n|silver_year       = 2017\n|gold_button       = yes\n|gold_year         = 2018\n|stats_update      = January 21, 2020\n|diamond_button    =\n|diamond_year      =\n}}\n\n'''Drew Gooden''' is an American comedian and filmmaker known for [[sketch comedy]] on [[Vine (service)|Vine]] and later [[criticism|commentary]] videos on [[YouTube]].\n\n==Career==\nGooden began his career on [[Vine (service)|Vine]], creating six-second [[sketch comedy|comedy sketches]].<ref name= Tiffany>{{cite news|author=Tiffany, Kaitlyn|date=December 23, 2019|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2019/12/clout-definition-meme-influencers-social-capital-youtube/603895/|title=Why Kids Online Are Chasing \u2018Clout\u2019|work=Atlantic Times}}</ref> After Vine was shut down by its parent company, [[Twitter]], Gooden began posting longer videos to YouTube. He currently has over 2 million subscribers.\n\nGooden has toured the United States with fellow YouTuber creator Kurtis Conner and twin Danny Gonzalez on their \"We Are Two Different People Tour\u201d, and was described as a theatrical comedy performance.<ref>{{cite news|author=McKenney, Kelcie|date=October 2, 2019|url=https://www.thepitchkc.com/youtubers-danny-gonzalez-and-drew-gooden-visit-kc-friday-on-their-we-are-two-different-people-tour/|title=YouTubers Danny Gonzalez and Drew Gooden visit KC Friday on their We Are Two Different People Tour|work=The Pitch}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/comedians-danny-gonzalez-drew-gooden-talk-tour-individuality-why-youtube-best-career-1457886|title=Danny Gonzalez and Drew Gooden talk tour, comedy and YouTube careers|last=EDT|first=Kelly Wynne On 9/5/19 at 2:39 PM|date=2019-09-05|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/09/drew-gooden-and-danny-gonzalez-the-john-olivers-of.html|title=Drew Gooden and Danny Gonzalez: The John Olivers of YouTube Culture|last=Wilbur|first=Brock|date=2019-09-09|website=pastemagazine.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\nDrew Gooden was also credited with his role in Camp Unplug, a show on Vine produced by [[Karyn Spencer]] and Jeremy Cabalona and written by Vine creators.<ref>https://shortyawards.com/9th/camp-unplug \"About Camp Unplug\"</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2016/06/27/vine-premieres-first-long-form-original-series-lauren-giraldo-cody-ko/|author=Weiss, Geoff|title=Vine Premieres Its First Long-Form Original Series, \u2018Camp Unplug\u2019, Starring Lauren Giraldo, Cody Ko|date=June 27, 2016|work=tubefilter}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Nominations==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Nominated\n!Award\n!Show\n!Result\n|-\n| 2016\n| Himself\n| [[Streamy Awards|Ensemble Cast]]\n| Camp Unplug\n| {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:American comedians]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Comedy YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Commentary YouTubers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American comedian and filmmaker|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{Notability|date=January 2020}}{{blp sourc